In the Shadow of Endangered Species: Three Cheetah Cubs Born in Iran
The world&#39;s fastest animal falls victim to brutal hunting, droughts and deadly road accidents across the Islamic Republic •
As a result, their number dropped to less than 20 cheetahs.
Three Asiatic cheetah cubs were recently born in the Islamic Republic of Iran.
This is a rare birth, which only slightly improves the tragic situation of the animal, which is in danger of extinction in the country due to droughts, poachers, and fatal road accidents.
This is the first birth of a cheetah in captivity in Iran.
It should be noted that the Islamic Republic is one of the last countries in the world where cheetahs still live in the wild.
The Iranian news agency IRNA reported that the veterinary team in charge of the Turan National Park in the northern province of Semnan decided on a cesarean birth in captivity.
It was also noted that less than 20 cheetahs have been recorded in seven different districts of the country recently.
Due to the danger of their extinction, the United Nations implemented a protection plan for them back in 2001.
Now, in Iran, they hope that the new cubs will be able to lead to an increase in the cheetah population in the future.
Last January, Iran&#39;s Deputy Minister of Environmental Affairs, Hassan Akbari, said that the country&#39;s cheetah population had dramatically decreased from 100 cheetahs in 2010 to just 12 cheetahs.
&quot;Their situation is extremely dire,&quot; said Akbari, noting that the cheetahs have fallen victim to drought in their habitat, hunting, and even traffic accidents.
The cheetah is considered the fastest animal in the world, capable of reaching speeds of about 100 km/h.
Cheetahs can be found in various places across the globe, from India to Senegal in West Africa.
Spotify wants to upgrade your car: We tested the Car Thing
Quietly, Spotify has also begun to try its luck in the world of hardware.
After years of development - Car Thing was unveiled and launched as a small experiment in the US •
We got our hands on the first device in Israel •
The vision: to make your old vehicles smart
The Car Thing is Spotify&#39;s first hardware product, and was built specifically to provide a solution for people with older vehicles.
A few weeks ago, I got an initial opportunity to try the new product, which is currently only available to a few testers in the US, here in Israel.
For me, the timing of the delivery was exceptional, as our home vehicle broke down and we had to drive for several days with a replacement vehicle with an old system.
After two weeks of playing around, I realized how the Car Thing could easily become an integral part of many people&#39;s systems.
On the other hand, with a long waiting list and uncertainty regarding a global launch, I believe that many will already prefer to use other solutions.
From idea to reality
Sometime in 2018, Spotify users began receiving an interesting offer in their email inbox - the opportunity to purchase a new device with voice control and fourth-generation connectivity, which would turn any old car system into a smart one.
The rumors slowly faded until a year later, when the Financial Times website revealed that the company was planning to soon introduce a new product for cars that simulates a smart radio with Bluetooth connectivity.
A few months later, these rumors returned to the headlines after the music service was updated with the car mode - the same one we know today from the app - which is activated as soon as the smartphone detects a connection to the car system.
Two years have passed since then.
After countless rumors and leaks, Spotify unveiled &quot;Car Thing,&quot; its smart system for vehicles, last April.
Spotify chose to release the new device in a very limited manner, with a long waiting list and many delays in shipments.
So of course, right after the press conference, I went to the website and registered.
Two months later, the long-awaited announcement arrived.
Reconnecting to the site will give me the opportunity to purchase the device with a little surprise - it won&#39;t cost me anything.
After another month of waiting, the delivery man finally knocked on my door, accompanied by a small box with the Spotify logo on it.
The Car Thing
First and foremost, Spotify&#39;s device impressed me greatly with its build quality.
It&#39;s slightly smaller than my iPhone 11 and has a larger, brighter, and sharper touchscreen on the front than I expected.
You will also find a round button and dial next to the screen that you can turn to navigate between the interface screens.
And despite the huge dial, which you can see in the pictures, the Car Thing manages to maintain a relatively thin profile and not stand out too much from the dashboard.
Personally, I would prefer the company to allow me to change the dial activity so that I could control the smartphone&#39;s volume, since I can also navigate using the touchscreen.
Maybe this will be possible in a future version update.
The device comes in a small, minimalist cardboard box, which includes, among other things, a USB Type C cable and various adapters for installing it.
Many of you probably remember how in the past we used to unplug our radios and hide them in a drawer after getting out of the car.
The Car Thing certainly brings back that feeling with its construction.
All adapters connected to the body of the device using a very strong magnet, which prevented it from falling even when driving on dirt roads.
In addition, along the entire top you can find small buttons, which can be easily configured to play various playlists or podcasts.
By long-pressing one of the buttons while listening, or by requesting it from the voice assistant, I defined several playlists that I listen to frequently and the radio program that I listen to every morning on the go.
In doing so, the feature made me feel like the Car Thing was more like a car radio than an extension of my smartphone.
Old Smart Car Body
After a fairly simple physical installation, I connected the Car Thing to power.
I was pleasantly surprised by the setup process.
The instructions were clear, connecting to the Spotify app took less than 5 minutes, and a few moments later I reached the home screen.
In fact, the device connects to the smartphone via Bluetooth and controls the app like a remote control, and can therefore copy all the information about our account from it.
This means that you will still have to connect your smartphone to the car, either via Bluetooth or an AUX cable, in order to listen to the music.
The home screen is familiar to all users of the app, as like the smartphone application, it emphasizes album art and playlists.
Also, on the home screen, like the one in the app, you can find music recommendations based on your taste, the search screen, and your personal library.
As mentioned, you can navigate between the different screens using the touchscreen or the manual dial.
Moreover, you can call the device&#39;s voice assistant at any given moment by saying &quot;Hey Spotify.&quot;
With it, you can play songs, playlists, albums, and even search for podcasts.
From my experience, it recognized my voice quite easily even when music was playing in the background and the air conditioner was blowing directly on the device.
This is probably thanks to the four microphones installed at the top.
It is important to note that currently the voice assistant does not support Hebrew, and as of the time of publication of the article, there is no information on when such an update will arrive.
So is it worth waiting for him?
My experience using the device was great, which is a positive surprise to me considering it is still in the initial release phase.
Even with intensive use on long trips, the device continued to work smoothly without disconnecting from my smartphone.
Still, there is occasionally a small stutter in the interface, but I believe Spotify will address such bugs with future version updates.
It&#39;s clear that the Swedish company has worked on it a lot in recent years, and of the various versions that have leaked online during this period, the design of the final product is probably my favorite.
Still, when I first saw the Car Thing, I wondered who exactly the company was trying to target.
After all, its activity amounts to controlling the application on the smartphone, and not much beyond that.
How is this different from buying a car stand for a few shekels and attaching it so that the smartphone is closer to us while driving?
This question is reinforced when considering that iPhones and Android devices are much more powerful than Spotify, and in most cases will give the user much more functionality.
Despite all this, the more I used Car Thing, the more I realized how it could improve the driving experience.
The ability to see Waze on my smartphone screen and control music on a completely different screen is one I&#39;ve learned to appreciate in the last two weeks.
One question remains - will Spotify even launch the device to the general public?
And if so, will it also be launched here in our small country?
The Swedish company is not saying much at the moment.
It didn&#39;t even share how many testers for the device it currently has running around the world, and how many it plans to add in the limited launch in the United States.
The only thing we know for sure is the price, which is expected to be $79 (about 255 shekels).
In the meantime, the Car Thing provides an initial glimpse into a concept that Spotify has been trying to crack for years.
Spotify Israel said there is currently no information on plans to launch the device in Israel.
