Have you recruited talent for the company?
This way you will ensure that competitors don&#39;t &quot;steal&quot; it from you.
The economy is still in a labor market that is largely dominated by workers, and this is doubly true when it comes to the most desirable employees - the talents •
Here are some tips to help you keep it in the workplace:
.
Despite the increase recorded last month, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to be one of the lowest in the world, and in the top ten among OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5% (150.6 thousand unemployed, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics).
In other words, the economy is still in a labor market that is largely dominated by workers, and this is doubly true when it comes to the most desirable workers - the talents.
With regard to those professionals and managers who constitute centers of proven knowledge, experience, and ability - trends in the labor market show that competition for them, the talents as they are called by employers, is still in full force.
What this means for employers is that in the current labor market situation, they do not have the luxury of resting on their laurels even a minute after recruiting a coveted talent, because as soon as he enters the company&#39;s doors, another company will already try to snatch him away.
In other words, the competition for talent is so fierce that even after being recruited, many will continue to receive a host of tempting job offers, with 30% of employees actually leaving within just a month of accepting the position and starting work.
This is why wise employers will immediately move from the talent recruitment phase to the talent retention phase, with the path beginning first and foremost with advance preparation and creativity already in the talent absorption process.
An efficient, structured, and thoughtful onboarding process will make the talent enthusiastic about their new workplace from day one and even look forward to what&#39;s to come.
Below are some tips on how to prepare and manage a proper onboarding process that will help retain new talent:
It&#39;s no secret - sharing and organizational readiness |
Share with the parties who will work with him on his recruitment, explain to them why he is essential and important to the company and the position, and how you see his contribution.
A new employee who arrives at a place where they are expected and their value is understood will feel welcome and strive to prove the expectations placed on them.
Knowledge is power - coordinating expectations |
On the very first day, they had a conversation with the talent to coordinate expectations.
Get to know his professional background and check where he sees himself in the future, so that you can present him with the diverse and unique tools that you and the workplace can provide him with to get there.
We are all people – personal introductions |
During the intake days, try to get to know the talent beyond his professional qualities and take an interest in his hobbies and interests.
A new employee who is shown interest in him and allowed to realize and express himself beyond the boundaries of his role will appreciate this and want to maintain it.
Curiosity advances |
Already at the onboarding stage, you can create an attractiveness that will make talent want to integrate quickly.
Do this not necessarily through a discussion of bonuses and benefits, but by exposing him to an exciting field or interesting technology, as this type of stimulus for creativity leads to curiosity and increased interest in the workplace.
Also, encourage the talent to voice his thoughts and opinions on the various projects in the company and make it clear to him that they are important to the organization.
The writer is the CEO of Manpower Israel – the largest placement and human resources company in Israel.
Electrification in your pocket: The cost of not closing coal-fired power plants in June - a billion shekels
Report by the Knesset Research and Information Center: Failure to close coal-fired power plants by the scheduled date of June 2022 is estimated at approximately one billion shekels
• The Electric Company: &quot;Fuel use policy is dictated primarily by the Ministry of Energy&quot;
.
The economic cost of not closing the coal-fired power plants on the scheduled date of June 2022 is estimated at approximately one billion shekels for 2022, according to a report by the Knesset Research and Information Center.
According to the report, this cost is reflected in the consumer electricity rate, which, as mentioned, is expected to increase in the coming months due to the increase in the price of coal.
In addition, in 2023, an additional excess amount of coal use of approximately 900,000 tons is expected, so this will be reflected in additional costs to the electricity sector for not closing the coal-fired plants, assuming that the price of natural gas remains significantly lower than the price of coal.
The report states that the significance of a reduction of approximately one billion shekels in the electricity tariff in 2022 was a reduction of approximately 4% in the electricity consumption tariff for the household consumer.
In other words, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about a billion shekels, and the total discount that could have been for the domestic consumer is about 4%.
It should be noted that as part of the reform of the electricity sector, it was decided, among other things, to establish a subsidiary of the Israel Electric Corporation, which will build units powered by natural gas, intended to replace the coal-fired units 4-1 at the Orot Rabin site.
Following this decision, a government decision was made in July 2018, determining that the operations of coal-fired generation units 4-1 at the Orot Rabin power plant should be discontinued.
The decision set timetables, so that the construction of the first natural gas unit will begin in January 2020 and its operation will begin in June 2022, and accordingly, the coal-fired production units 4-1 will also cease operation at this time.
The Israel Electric Corporation responded: &quot;Fuel use policy is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy.
In accordance with the ministry&#39;s decisions, a policy of reducing the use of coal to the minimum possible has been implemented in Israel for several years, even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas.&quot;
Paying the price: everything you need to know ahead of interest rate hikes
Constant decrees: Next week the interest rate on the shekel is expected to rise by half a percent •
How much will the mortgage payment cost?
And what is recommended to do? •
All the answers
The worsening inflation in Israel, which has already reached a rate of more than 4% in the past year, will force the Bank of Israel to raise the interest rate on the shekel as early as next week.
Analysts&#39; estimates speak of an increase rate ranging between 0.25% and 0.5%.
If the interest rate does indeed rise by half a percentage point, it will already be 1.25%, the highest level in nine years.
This is after interest rates in the economy were close to zero for years.
The sharp increase in interest rates increases the cost of mortgage repayments by hundreds of shekels and places a drastic burden on households.
With the help of Shai Tzror, a mortgage expert, we examined how much more we will pay and what is recommended to be done now.
If the interest rate increases by half a percent, how much will the monthly mortgage payment increase?
On a mortgage of 1.2 million shekels, which consists of a 40% prime interest rate, the monthly repayment will increase by 125 shekels.
How much has the average mortgage cost increased since the beginning of the year?
This is a significantly sharper increase since the beginning of the year.
This is because the interest rates in the other tracks that make up a mortgage (and not just the prime track) have also increased - in the index-linked track and the fixed-interest track.
If the interest rate does indeed rise by half a percent, the increase in price will amount, according to Tzror&#39;s estimate, to about 620 shekels on a mortgage of about 1.2 million shekels.
The Prime route (40% in this route) will complete a price increase of approximately 280 shekels, assuming there will be an increase of another 0.5% next month.
The variable interest rate track linked to the index (26.7% in this track) will compensate for an increase in price of about 120 shekels.
The fixed interest rate track - not index-linked (33.3% in this track) will increase in price by 220 shekels.
So what is recommended to do today?
For those who have a mortgage that is mostly index-linked, Tzror recommends considering recycling to non-index-linked tracks.
For mortgage holders whose monthly repayments have increased significantly and are finding it difficult to meet their repayments, he recommends considering refinancing their mortgage and rescheduling it for a longer period.
This is to reduce payments despite the increase in interest, as it is always better to meet repayments and not be insolvent.
Regarding new mortgage borrowers, he highly recommends getting to know the different routes and adapting the mortgage to their financial capabilities.
Likewise, in the future, when interest rates drop, they will be able to refinance their mortgage with minimal early repayment fees.
Regarding buyers of apartments from a contractor - Tzror recommends making advance payments to the contractor and taking out a mortgage now.
It should be taken into account that the &quot;construction input index&quot; significantly increases the price of the property even after the purchase contract has been signed.
The residential construction input price index rose by 6.6% in the past year.
In light of the increase in this index, the Banking Supervision Department announced yesterday that it is considering requiring the creation of a mechanism that would allow for the inclusion of linkages within mortgages, but the final decision on the matter has not yet been made.
The price of fuel is rising - and Israelis will have to pay more than 8 shekels per liter in July
The Ministry of Energy announced that the new price per liter of 95 octane gasoline will be 8.08 shekels •
At the same time, the reduction of half a NIS per liter in the tax on diesel will be extended until the end of 2022.
A decade-long record: The price of gasoline will jump by 36 agorot per liter - and will stand at more than 8 shekels per liter starting July 1.
The new price per liter of 95 octane gasoline will be 8.08, and those who wish to enjoy full service will be required to pay an additional 21 cents per liter.
At the same time, the reduction of half a shekel per liter in the diesel tax will be extended until the end of 2022, the Tax Authority announced.
As mentioned, the price increase is due to the continued rise in oil prices, due to the war between Russia and Ukraine and the rise in the dollar exchange rate.
If it weren&#39;t for the half-shekel discount that the government has been subsidizing since April, the price of fuel would have exceeded an all-time high - 8.25 shekels per liter.
The discount expires at the end of July, and the Tax Authority and the Treasury are currently promoting the publication for public comment of an order extending the reduction in the tax on gasoline, which stands at half a shekel per liter, until August 9.
Also, starting August 10, an additional reduction of another half a shekel will be determined, so that only from this date will the price of a liter of gasoline be reduced by one shekel, until November 15, 2022.
This was reported by the Tax Authority.
&quot;We have reached a situation where I don&#39;t remember five consecutive months of a surplus in state revenue.
We started a few months ago with the issue of reducing the tax on diesel.
We have been working for a week on extending the excise tax on gasoline and diesel for another four months - instead of half a shekel per shekel.
This is good for the industry and the citizen.
If we lower it, it will affect inflation, make production cheaper, and ease the cost of living.
&quot;As Minister of Finance, despite the election campaign, I intend to focus on this first,&quot; Minister Lieberman said at the Israel Democracy Institute&#39;s Hurwitz Conference on Economy and Society.
As of today, more than half of the price of fuel is taxes collected by the government (excise tax and VAT) - and this is a high taxation rate compared to most developed countries.
The price of fuel has a dramatic impact on the cost of living in the economy - because it affects both household and business expenses, the prices of public transportation and flights, transportation costs, and more.
For the third time in a row: Ashdod - the most business-friendly city
Petah Tikva ranked second in the Ministry of Economy&#39;s Doing Business ranking •
Followed by: Rehovot, Ashkelon and Rishon LeZion •
Minister Barabibai: &quot;Corona has highlighted the importance of local government in business development&quot;
.
Ashdod is the friendliest city for small and medium-sized businesses.
This is the third year in a row - this is what the Doing Business in Local Authorities Index of the Agency for Small and Medium-sized Businesses in the Ministry of Economy and Industry found, which ranked local authorities.
In second place is the city of Petah Tikva and in third place is Rehovot.
Following them, in order, are: Ashkelon, Rishon LeZion, Tel Aviv-Yafo, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Beer Sheva, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya and Bnei Brak.
The agency compiles the Local Authorities Index.
This is the fifth time and its goal is to serve as a tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance with other authorities on a variety of parameters, as well as to analyze its performance in the areas in which it is active.
The index is based on several parameters that are examined in each authority, which examine the level of &quot;friendliness&quot; of the authority to businesses located within its jurisdiction.
The index divides authorities into three size groups according to the number of residents, as a local authority of up to 50,000 residents is not similar to a local authority of more than 150,000 residents.
Tel Aviv soared this year
The index is updated once a year and weighs four different ratings in each local authority: business satisfaction, accessibility to tenders, accessibility of information, and property taxes.
The ranking shows that Ramat Gan fell from second place to eighth place, Bat Yam fell from fourth place to 12th place, and Netanya fell from fifth place to 13th place.
A drop in rating does not mean that the authority&#39;s service to businesses has deteriorated, and in many cases it results from the fact that other authorities&#39; service to businesses has improved more and they have risen in rating, while the authority that dropped in rating has improved its services to businesses less.
Among those moving up in the ranking are Petah Tikva, which rose from sixth place to second place, and Rehovot, which rose from 12th place to third place.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from fourth place to 11th place in 2019, improved in 2021 and rose to sixth place.
&quot;Business - an engine of growth&quot;
The ranking shows that Nof HaGalil leads among local authorities with between 50 and 150 thousand residents.
Following it are Kiryat Motzkin, Mateh Binyamin, Modi&#39;in-Maccabim-Reut, Kfar Saba, Ra&#39;anana, Nahariya, Karmiel, Afula and Hod Hasharon.
Tiberias is located in 28th and last place.
&quot;The index is designed to encourage local authorities to make things easier for small and medium-sized businesses, starting from the date the business opens and throughout its activities with the authorities,&quot; says Minister of Economy and Industry, Orna Barbiebai.
&quot;Businesses constitute a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy and are responsible for approximately 50% of business output and approximately 60% of those employed in the economy.&quot;
The development of small businesses is in the public interest of all of us, but the local authority has a direct influence on the businesses located there.
&quot;The coronavirus has emphasized the importance of local government, and we have seen that authorities that have acted and encouraged the promotion of small businesses and found creative solutions for them have become the first government interface for them.&quot;
Ran Kuwaiti, Director of the Agency for Small and Medium-Sized Businesses at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: &quot;Local authorities play a central and essential role in the ability of businesses in their field to thrive and flourish.
&quot;In the last two years, as we deal with the Corona crisis, authorities have had a greater role in helping businesses survive in their field and in general.&quot;
2021 in the mail: 20 packages per household - and a jump in their weight
46.6 million packages arrived in Israel during 2021 - similar to 2020 •
The average weight per package is 435 grams - a 36% jump compared to 2020 •
Busiest month: December, when the average package weight was 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million postal packages arrived in Israel, almost 20 packages on average per household - this is according to Israel Post data obtained by &quot;Israel Today.&quot;
The number of packages that arrived in 2021 is similar to 2020, when 46.5 million packages arrived in Israel, and lower than 2019, when 61.6 million packages arrived.
However, this year there was a jump of more than 36% in the weight of packages arriving from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products arrived in Israel from abroad, a 36% jump compared to 14,860 tons in 2020, and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in consumption habits
The average weight per package jumped by 60% in two years - from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The surge in package weight is mainly influenced by two major trends, both on the seller&#39;s and the buyer&#39;s side: The major shopping sites abroad are consolidating items into one shipment and no longer sending each product from the &quot;shopping cart&quot; in a separate package.
From the Israeli consumer&#39;s perspective, the rapid delivery of shipments, within a few days of ordering, supports the purchase of more everyday products such as clothing and gifts, which buyers are interested in receiving soon after making the purchase.
In 2021, as in 2020 and 2019, the month in which the most packages from abroad arrived with the highest weight and the highest number of items was December, with 4.2 million packages with a total weight of 2,200 tons.
In December, the average weight per package was 524 grams, 20% higher than the annual average weight.
Black Friday effect
More packages arrived in December than any other month, likely due to November shopping holidays, such as Chinese Singles&#39; Day, Black Friday, and Cyber Monday.
Large orders begin arriving in Israel between one and two weeks after purchase.
Research: Most employees in the economy are unaware that they can receive tax refunds
Many employees receive money from the state, which can amount to tens of thousands of shekels.
Have you changed jobs?
Did you go on unpaid leave?
Did you move from the city to a town?
You may be entitled to receive a significant amount in a simple procedure •
All the details - inside
Most employees are unaware that they are entitled to tax refunds, which can add up to large amounts.
The State Comptroller noted in a report from about two months ago that two million employees are entitled to tax refunds of 3.6 billion shekels, which means that you should also check whether you are entitled to receive tax refunds.
Many employees can receive a high amount, as four out of five employees are eligible for tax refunds.
In practice, however, several tens of thousands of employees submit applications each year.
If you think that these funds will go down the drain anyway, think again: employees can apply to the Income Tax for refunds for six years back.
Tax:On conducted in-depth research among 4,000 of its customers regarding tax returns during 2020.
The company has over 30,000 customers, so the sample reflects their distribution in terms of population groups, gender, age, and geography.
The data shows that during 2020, due to the outbreak of the Corona crisis and the spending of hundreds of thousands of workers on unpaid leave, a number of significant changes occurred, centered on a 15% increase in the average amount of the refund to a household, which stood at 4,300 shekels per year.
The reason is that the social security contributions are lower than salaries, and therefore a gap is created between what the employee paid in taxes and what he actually needs.
By the way, the highest refund received by a company customer in 2020 was NIS 121,054 for refunds over the last 6 years.
What can you get tax refunds for?
One of the reasons for receiving tax refunds is a change in workplace.
81% of people who changed jobs during the year received a tax refund in an average amount of 2,943 shekels.
Another reason is maternity leave.
The data shows that 74% of women who gave birth and were on maternity leave for over 16 weeks were entitled to an average refund of 3,538 shekels for that year.
Another reason for reimbursement is donations.
100% of people who donate and pay taxes received a refund.
Another factor for repayment is failure to record credit points for alimony. 63%
Of the divorced, no credit point was updated for alimony, and therefore the tax refund for each year for which such a credit point was not updated is 2,616 shekels.
Due to unemployment - spending on unemployment benefits: 93% of those who went on sick leave or unemployment and who earned over 12,000 shekels received a tax refund of 4,021 shekels for that year.
Additional reasons for tax refunds are: refunds for life insurance payments, mortgage life insurance, refunds for qualifying settlements, refunds for losses in securities, failure to register credit points for men for childbirth, and distribution of tax refunds by geographic location.
- 94% of people who deposited for personal life insurance or for taking out a mortgage were eligible for a tax refund.
In a study conducted on every million shekels of a 25-year mortgage, the cumulative tax refund for the period is over 20,000 shekels for the entire mortgage period.
100% of those moving to a qualifying locality received a tax refund for the year of the move, since confirmation of residency in a qualifying locality is only granted 12 months after the resident becomes a qualifying resident, and thus in effect the first year full tax is paid.
79% of customers holding securities were eligible for a tax refund for the aforementioned years.
However, it is important for anyone who holds securities to check every year, since losses are not rolled over from year to year, but only through filing a report.
56% of men who have a child do not record credit points in the year of birth on their paycheck.
The repayment rate can reach tens of thousands of shekels over 6 years.
This is a phenomenon that exists mainly in the Arab sector.
Tax:on CEO Tal Carmon: &quot;The coronavirus crisis has caused the Israeli wage earner to become much more active.
He is interested, checks and demands what he is entitled to in income tax refunds.
It turns out that the fact that hundreds of thousands of Israelis have been sitting at home, on sick leave or after being laid off, for months has caused many employees to take a closer look at what they deserve from the state.
&quot;It is important to know that today all procedures for receiving tax refunds can be carried out digitally, easily and simply, without the bureaucracy that deterred many in the past.&quot;
The job market: fewer job candidates, more pay
Oljobs Report 2021 Summary: Top Demand - Jobs Without Experience •
The volume of jobs offered increased by 50% •
&quot;Looking for a job, but not storming the market&quot;
In the year that just ended, there was a 15% decrease in the number of resumes sent, and an average of only 23 candidates competed for each position, compared to 41 candidates the previous year - this is according to a report by the Oljobs website summarizing 2021, on the Corona crisis and its effects on the labor market in Israel.
According to the report, job seekers were mainly interested in job-rich fields such as administration and sales, for which 1,738,485 resumes were sent.
However, jobs without experience led the way in demand with more than 38,000 searches - probably following the return of young people without professional experience to search for immediate work, after the end of unemployment benefits.
The number of searches for sales and administration was 35,000 and 32,000 (respectively), drivers and couriers had 11,000 searches, and security had slightly less than 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the Corona crisis, wages in 2021 increased by 2% compared to 2020, and the average wage in Israel was 11,675 shekels gross.
The average monthly salary in the software field was 17,915 shekels, and in information systems analysis it was 17,140 shekels.
However, there was a wage gap of more than 2,000 shekels between the center and the periphery: in the center of the country it was 12,500 shekels on average, compared to 10,795 in the north and 10,135 shekels in the south.
From a gender perspective, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained by the type of work and the number of hours worked, remained at 36%.
Men earned 13,295 shekels, compared to women&#39;s wages of 9,740 shekels.
Trying to get back into the groove
On the business side, there was broad-based growth in almost all sectors of the economy, and businesses craved working hands.
Thus, the job offer increased by 50% and recorded a record of more than 40,000 jobs on Alljobs.
A survey conducted by the site among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their economic status in 2022, 30% of whom indicated their intention to increase total hiring, but 72% understand that they will have difficulty doing so this year.
