The number of institutional tests carried out in the community (excluding tests of returnees from abroad, MI) is low, standing at less than 20,000 tests on a weekly average.
&quot;The low volume of testing makes it difficult to identify and understand morbidity trends.&quot;
State Comptroller&#39;s Report: The actual budget in most years of the Pharmaceutical Basket Committee&#39;s activity is smaller than the recommended budget
According to the report by Matanyahu Engelman, for more than 20 years of the basket&#39;s operation, the Ministry of Health did not supervise the committee&#39;s activities.
The report also states that the minutes of the meetings are published with significant delay, if at all.
The auditor also recommends increasing the transparency of the subcommittee&#39;s activities – and updating the basket work procedures.
Another deficiency found concerns the fact that since the committee began its activities, the Ministry of Health has not requested reports from the health funds on the extent of use and utilization of the drugs in the basket - which would have made it possible to analyze and monitor the budget given to them.
The Pharmaceutical Basket Committee is one of the public committees that has the most influence on our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the committee decides on new medications that will be provided to the public free of charge through health funds - but a new report by the State Comptroller published today (Tuesday) warns that it has been operating for more than 20 years without any control reports on its activities and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council supervising and examining its activities.
&quot;Israel Hayom&quot; reporter Ran Reznik adds that the State Comptroller&#39;s investigation was conducted following the ongoing exposures in &quot;Israel Hayom&quot; about the shortcomings of the pharmaceutical basket.
According to Matanyahu Engelman&#39;s report, he recommends &quot;making corrections and improvements in the process of expanding the basket, which will lead to better utilization of the health services basket budget to which the public is entitled.&quot;
Throughout the years of the existence of the mechanism for adding to the basket of medicines, between 1998 and 2021, medicines totaling eight billion shekels were added to the state budget - with the addition varying annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels.
In 2019, 2020, and 2021, applications were submitted to add approximately 800 new drugs and technologies to the healthcare services basket, at a total annual cost of more than two billion shekels.
In practice, the budget allocated to expand the basket was smaller than the scope of the requests.
In most of the years of the committee&#39;s operation (90% of the time), the amount of the budgetary increase was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired increase rate.
The auditor notes that it is necessary to examine and regulate the amount of the annual increment in order to allow for certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman also noted that &quot;the transparency model in basket work is lacking.&quot;
For example, the working procedure of the Basket Committee states that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published with a delay of 109-160 days, with sometimes the minutes of the final meetings not being published at all.
&quot;The delay in publishing the protocols harms the transparency of decisions; as a result, the ability of the proposers – patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies – to submit repeat applications as soon as possible and relevant may be impaired, after they have learned lessons from the rejection of their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and revised their proposals, and reassessed their feasibility for acceptance in the next round,&quot; the auditor noted in the report.
&quot;The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols in accordance with the schedules set out in the procedure.&quot;
Out of thousands of submissions – only one economic comment was submitted
Another criticism of Engelman concerns the preliminary process of evaluating the technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The auditor found that approximately half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the rejection.
Another deficiency concerns the activities of the subcommittee on the drug basket, which is closed to the media and the public, and where patient numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The auditor recommends including a public representative or examining the possibility of publishing the discussions to the public without confidential commercial details.
The procedure by which the Health Services Basket Committee operates states that &quot;an economic evaluation must be submitted&quot; for a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic evaluation has been submitted out of thousands of submissions – and the committee makes its decisions without an economic evaluation.
For example, requests were submitted to the basket committee for the years 2019-2021 to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
The report revealed that the requests were not accompanied by economic assessments, including an estimate of the amount that could have been saved due to reducing the damage caused by diseases resulting from obesity or due to the ability to avoid gastric bypass surgery.
It also appears that the decisions of the Drug Basket Committee are not consistent with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
For example, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparation for the treatment of the increase in chronic diseases as goals, but in the framework of the decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The Comptroller also warns that since 2011, the drug basket also includes services that are not the responsibility of the health funds, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccinations, which are provided by the Ministry of Health (&quot;the third supplement&quot;).
This is because the legal framework for this step is only regulated retrospectively.
In the last six years, 74 million shekels from the addition to the drug basket have been used for these services.
Engelman recommends that the Ministry of Health update the basket work procedures and also determine whether a separate financial supplement is needed for these services.
About a third of the new drugs that enter the drug basket are defined as &quot;drugs without additional cost,&quot; the use of which does not cost the health insurance funds an additional amount because they replace existing treatment.
The auditor suggests examining the possibility of these drugs being discussed in a different, abbreviated track, so that it would be possible to update the drug basket several times a year and not just once a year.
There is no supervision over the use of particularly expensive medications.
The audit also shows that since the work of the basket committee began 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds to report or monitor the extent of use and utilization of the medicines in the basket, information that could have allowed the ministry to analyze and monitor the budget given to the funds.
Over the years, only two reports have been published, covering the years 2006-2009, and even these were published with considerable delay (the last one was published this year and dealt with budget utilization in the years 2007-2009).
&quot;The delay in conducting tests may lead to difficulty in collecting and analyzing data, irrelevance of the conclusions emerging from the test after such a long period, suboptimal pricing by the subcommittee, and making decisions based on inconclusive findings,&quot; the report states.
Likewise, the ministry does not audit or supervise the use of particularly expensive medications and has not conducted any lessons learned.
These are 10 drugs that accounted for 62% of the addition to the basket (1.7 billion shekels in 2016-2021).
Regarding this, the Comptroller wrote: &quot;It is recommended that the Ministry of Health conduct individual inspections of these drugs and technologies and analyze the extent of their use compared to estimates.
&quot;Controls and analysis will allow us to draw systemic conclusions about the work process of the basket committee and the subcommittee, and about the manner in which estimates are prepared when pricing medicines and technologies, and to improve them.&quot;
