Prof. Galia Rahav, Director of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Sheba |
About the late Prof. Marvin Shapira
The meeting that opened my eyes - and changed my life
If I hadn&#39;t met the late Prof. Marvin Shapira, who was the director of the infectious diseases unit at Hadassah Hospital, I would probably have remained a specialist in internal medicine.
He is the one who made me love the field of infectious diseases and influenced me to pursue it.
I met him in the corridors of Hadassah, back then in the 1980s.
I never thought for a moment that I would leave internism, as I loved the care of the patient himself; but Prof. Shapira showed me that the field of infectious diseases is also reflected in neurology, internism, and basically in every field.
I thank him for bringing me into this field.
Throughout, I loved his investigative approach, an approach that gets to the root of the problem.
The discussions with him were analytical and logical.
He was a doctor with every fiber of his soul, who loved his patients and taught me not to take things for granted and to examine everything in depth.
He was a genuine and honest person, devoid of ego, qualities that I really liked about him.
Initially, when I was asked to choose a doctor who was a role model for me and influenced me the most, I intended to choose my father, the late Dr. Yosef Rakover, a Holocaust survivor who served as a doctor in a partisan unit.
He was an amazing doctor, who influenced me to go into medicine - but he also reminds me of Marvin Shapiro.
Both, for example, coined proverbs that doctors still use today - such as &quot;Tissue is the disease,&quot; meaning that taking a biopsy of tissue from the affected organ allows us to know which medications to give; or &quot;Once you use it, you lose it,&quot; which is intended to explain that overuse of antibiotics leads to bacteria becoming resistant to them.
The late Prof. Shapira was married to a physiotherapist who worked at Hadassah and had two daughters.
He passed away about a year ago, and when I visited his family on Shabbat, I cried.
He was something - a witty and smart epidemiologist, who volunteered for everything.
He never complained, not even during his serious illness.
He was one of the first doctors on the team to treat epidemics, and he is sorely missed during this period.
If he were with us today, I&#39;m sure I would consult with him, and I&#39;m sure he would be one of the leaders of the team handling epidemics.
Published by: Meital Yasur Beit-Or
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh, Director of Soroka Hospital |
About the late Prof. Shaul Suknik
A teacher and friend who supported me and raised generations of doctors
.
I first met the late Prof. Shaul Suknik when I was a fourth-year medical student, and I came to a rotation in internal medicine in the fourth internal medicine department that he directed.
Later, I returned to the department for a rotation in my sixth year, and I did my medical school final thesis under his supervision, writing a computer simulation on a patient with polyarthritis (inflammation of multiple joints).
Shaul influenced every significant juncture in my professional life over the course of 20 years, and was the most significant person in shaping my image as a doctor; not only professionally, but also - and most importantly - from a personal and human perspective.
During my internship, I was debating between family medicine and internal medicine, and I consulted with him about choosing a specialization.
In the end, I chose to specialize in internal medicine with him in Soroka.
During my internship, he provided me with constant guidance, in a variety of ways - in scientific writing (sorry Shaul, I wasn&#39;t persistent enough), in communicating with patients, in working in a multidisciplinary team - an area in which the department excelled - and, in fact, in every aspect related to medicine.
To this day, I recognize in myself, as a doctor and as a manager, characteristics that come from Saul.
When I finished my internship and was debating whether to go for a period of training abroad, Shaul pushed and guided me, and helped me with letters of recommendation and advice on how to proceed.
The training period was a very important time for my professional development, and without Shaul&#39;s support and encouragement, it&#39;s not certain that it would have happened.
Upon my return, when I received an offer to join the hospital management, Shaul was again the one who supported and assisted.
Later, we successfully navigated complex periods together in the Internal Medicine Division.
Shaul knew how to wonderfully combine the roles of teacher, principal, friend, and teammate, without his various roles interfering with each other.
I strive to be as successful as he is in this special combination.
He raised generations of students, interns, and residents, who are currently throughout the Israeli medical system, and who perpetuate his memory and work through their excellent work.
I am honored to be included in this group.
Published by: Ilya Yegorov
Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev, Director of Schneider Children&#39;s Center |
About Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld
The man who taught me medicine, and especially listening.
Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld, founder and former director of the Intensive Care Unit at Schneider Children&#39;s Medical Center, taught me to be an intensive care physician, but more than that - he taught me to think.
The obvious thing I learned from him is to take care of the most complex, the sickest children.
The children, some of whom were healthy just a moment ago, are now between life and death.
The obvious thing is to have very difficult conversations, perhaps the most difficult, with families who never imagined they would find themselves in these complex situations in an intensive care unit with their children.
Sounds strange, but it&#39;s obvious.
But I learned even more significant and profound things from him.
Looking back, because I am a doctor who is a manager and a manager who is a doctor, it is clear to me today that the connection between the worlds is clear; the education I received from Dr. Sheinfeld connects them.
Dr. Sheinfeld taught me to listen attentively to many things: to listen to the children, to listen to the monitor, to listen to the nurses, to the teams caring for both young and old, and to listen to the parents.
All of this needs to be done not only to communicate more correctly and successfully, but also to constantly collect a wealth of information that can prevent the next deterioration.
Preventive processes in the care of children exist everywhere, and of course also in intensive care.
Listening and dialogue inspire deeper understanding, both on the part of the care team and on the part of the patients and their families.
My understanding today as a manager is that these insights are also true when looking at an entire system.
The deeper and more rigorous the understanding, which incorporates all the involved parties into the discourse, the more accurate the decision-making process will be, tailored to the situation, and most importantly - early enough to prevent future, immediate or distant damage.
This is why Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld is much more than an inspirational figure to me.
He is a man who taught me a lot about medicine, but mostly taught me to think quickly and accurately, to listen - and then to apply.
