Medical malpractice during the various stages of childbirth
In order to win damages, plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that the damage was caused by that negligence.
Birth is one of the most joyful and exciting events in a family&#39;s life.
However, unfortunately, sometimes births end in serious harm to the mother or newborn as a result of negligence on the part of the medical team.
In cases where the birth ended in physical injury, to the newborn or the mother, it is appropriate to examine the sequence of events that led to the injury and even consider seeking legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in medical malpractice will examine whether there were any flaws in the conduct of the medical team during the various stages of childbirth that caused the damage, and if deemed appropriate, will seek advice from a medical expert in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every error in treatment on the part of the medical team amounts to negligence (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily indicate that its management was negligent.
When, then, is it negligence?
When the doctor&#39;s error resulted from a lack of skill or deviated from the reasonable level of caution, and the lack of skill and deviation from the accepted level of caution caused harm to the patient that would not have been caused if the doctor had not acted in this way.
In this article, we will examine the different stages of childbirth, explain the complications that may occur during each stage, and when they amount to medical malpractice.
The phase of the axes
The labor phase lasts on average between 8 and 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix gradually opens (in order to allow the passage of the fetus during birth) and at the end of the process should reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
Most cases of medical negligence during labor involve failure to identify fetal distress prior to birth, which caused harm to the newborn, sometimes manifesting as cerebral palsy.
Cerebral Palsy (CP):
Cerebral palsy may be caused by failure to recognize or delay in recognizing perinatal asphyxia, which is manifested by a failure to supply oxygen to the fetus&#39;s brain tissue.
In general, monitoring the condition of the mother and correctly interpreting the fetal heart monitor should lead to early identification of the development of fetal distress, allowing the medical team to act quickly and rescue the newborn before it is irreversibly damaged.
Cases in which the medical team ignores signs indicating that the fetus is suffering from a lack of oxygen, or the team does not correctly interpret the data in front of them, especially the fetal monitor, or responds late to distress expressed on the monitor, may constitute negligence.
Cerebral palsy may also be caused by umbilical cord prolapse and by a uterine rupture that was not detected in time.
Even in these difficult events, it is appropriate to inquire whether the medical team acted appropriately.
For example, Attorney Anna Reif Liganza, from the Caspi Sror &amp; Co. law firm, which specializes in representing victims of medical malpractice, says that her office handled a claim by a child who was injured during birth after the midwife ruptured the amniotic sac when the fetus&#39;s head was too high, thereby leading to umbilical cord prolapse (when the umbilical cord precedes the fetus&#39;s head) and damage to the oxygen supply to the fetus&#39;s brain (as a result of pressure from the fetus&#39;s head on the umbilical cord), resulting in the child being born with severe neurological damage.
In another case, an attorney said that her office filed a lawsuit due to serious medical negligence by the staff of the maternity ward at a large hospital who, during the birth, did not recognize clear signs at the time that warranted a real suspicion that the woman in labor was suffering from a uterine rupture in the area of the surgical scar from her previous pregnancy.
The fetus, which was ejected through the tear in its mother&#39;s uterus into the abdominal cavity, suffered severe fetal distress until it was rescued at a late stage when it was on the verge of death.
Due to the severe fetal suffering during his birth, the child suffered a complex neurological disability.
We emphasize that in order to win compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal connection between the negligence of the medical team that led to the failure to identify the asphyxiation and the damage caused to the newborn, meaning that the damage was caused due to the aforementioned negligence and not by any other reason or factor.
The examination of the causal relationship will be carried out by examining medical indicators that, according to the medical literature, only when they are present does a causal relationship exist between the asphyxiation and the brain injury.
Among other things, the indicators of the acidity level in the fetus&#39;s blood, its Apgar scores, the existence of neurological and systemic damage, and more are examined.
Fetal death
The active labor stage
The active labor stage begins when the cervix reaches a diameter of 10 centimeters and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical phase.
Delaying birth and avoiding cesarean section
In some cases, dysfunctional labor develops, that is, a lack of progress in the active labor process.
In such situations, it is customary to perform a cesarean section, in order to prevent various damages that may be caused to the fetus due to the delay in birth.
&quot;There are cases in which failure to perform a cesarean section on time may cause irreversible damage to the fetus,&quot; Attorney Reif-Liganze explained to us.
&quot;For example, we handled a medical malpractice claim involving the death of a newborn caused by a significant delay in performing a cesarean section.
Contrary to all recognized medical practice, the medical team failed to identify fetal distress and perform a cesarean section despite the extremely slow progress of labor.
The delay in performing the surgery caused multi-system damage to the newborn, which ultimately led to her death shortly after birth.&quot;
Vacuum birth negligence
In situations where the mother or fetus is in significant danger and requires an extremely rapid termination of labor, a vacuum delivery (empty suction) is sometimes performed.
In this process, a &quot;dome&quot; is attached to the fetus&#39;s head using a vacuum and the fetus is forcefully pulled out.
Naturally, this operation involves dangers and may cause damage to both the fetus and the mother, and therefore requires great caution, precision, and skill.
In these events, medical negligence may manifest itself in the doctor not adhering to the mandatory instructions and performing the procedure despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the fetal head is too high in the pelvis, or performing it for a longer time than permitted, or when, despite the failure of many attempts, the doctor continues and repeats the procedure more than the permitted number of attempts.
In these cases, if the negligent vacuum operation caused harm to the newborn - among other things, it may cause cranial damage and bleeding that may cause the development of brain damage - there is a case for filing a tort claim.
ERB paralysis
Erb&#39;s palsy is a congenital nerve injury to the brachial plexus (a nerve junction that connects the spine to the upper part of the shoulder), and when it occurs during childbirth, it is appropriate to check whether the damage occurred as a result of negligence on the part of the obstetric team.
The injury manifests itself in weakness of the hand muscles and can lead to complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in delivering the newborn due to the occurrence of &#39;shoulder breech&#39; - an obstetric emergency that occurs when the fetus&#39;s shoulders become trapped inside the birth canal after its head has emerged.
When should you suspect that paralysis was caused by medical malpractice?
In cases where the assessment of the fetus&#39;s weight indicates that it is a macrosomic fetus, meaning that it is expected to be born weighing more than 4.5 kilograms, and in accordance with guidelines, it is preferable for the mother to deliver the baby by cesarean section.
When the newborn&#39;s weight is over 4 kilograms, a cesarean section should be considered in light of risk factors, including gestational diabetes and prolonged second stage of labor.
In the event that the medical team ignores an abnormal fetal weight assessment or additional risk factors and chooses to continue with a vaginal birth and the risk of shoulder dislocation and ERB paralysis is realized, there is a reasonable possibility that this is medical negligence.
Indeed, in AA 2694/90, the Supreme Court ruled that &quot;the risk that shoulder stenosis will occur during childbirth can be predicted in advance with some degree of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder stenosis, where there is a concern that it will occur, is to perform a cesarean section.&quot;
Placental abruption stage
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its expulsion occurs due to uterine contractions after the birth of the newborn and is accompanied by bleeding.
In most cases, the process lasts up to half an hour from the moment the baby is born and most often occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical team.
After the placenta is delivered, the medical team will check whether it came out intact or whether parts of the placenta remain in the uterus.
During this stage, complications may occur that could cause serious harm to the mother.
One of the known complications resulting from placenta remnants remaining in the uterus is called &quot;Asherman&#39;s syndrome&quot;, scarring of the uterine wall as a result of inflammation caused by placenta remnants remaining in the uterus, a phenomenon that damages the uterine lining in a way that prevents pregnancy from implanting.
Therefore, in cases where the medical team did not recognize that there were remnants of the placenta remaining or did not take all measures to prevent damage to the uterine lining despite the suspicion of remnants of the placenta in the uterus, it may be a case of medical negligence and the case deserves a thorough examination by an experienced lawyer in the field.
Death of the mother
The death of a mother during childbirth is a fairly rare event.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy to the entire family unfortunately becomes the most tragic event for it.
In some cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the mother in time or responds too late to such bleeding.
&quot;For example...&quot;, Attorney Reif-Ligenze told us, &quot;our firm filed a lawsuit involving the death of a woman in labor, when in that case the medical team ignored and did not respond to the woman&#39;s worrying vital signs, waited for long hours, and delayed diagnosing massive and uncontrollable bleeding that occurred as a known complication of the underlying disease from which she suffered.&quot;
&quot;In another case...&quot;, said Attorney Reif-Liganza, &quot;our firm represented the relatives of a woman who died after giving birth to twins due to bleeding that originated from a cesarean section that was not sewn properly.
&quot;In that case, the woman in labor complained of severe pain and weakness after the surgery, but the medical team did not properly address her complaints and clinical condition, responding late only after her body systems began to collapse, which led to her death.&quot;
Loss of uterus
In serious cases, medical malpractice during childbirth may lead to a hysterectomy, says Attorney Reif Lingze: &quot;Our firm handled a lawsuit against a hospital based on a hysterectomy due to medical malpractice after childbirth.
In that case, the woman giving birth, a 31-year-old woman, lost her uterus due to a lack of proper treatment for massive bleeding observed by the medical team after delivery, and yet no timely action was taken to prevent the damage.
What are the compensations awarded in claims for medical negligence during childbirth?
Newborn compensation for injury due to medical negligence during childbirth includes many damage components, with the most significant amounts being awarded for pain and suffering, nursing and paid care, loss of wages and pension for the injured person and even his parents, and additional damage components.
The compensation awarded to an injured minor for lost wages and pensions is calculated in most cases based on the average wage in the economy.
The compensation also includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitation equipment, the cost of adapting housing to the baby&#39;s needs, mobility, and more.
&quot;The amount of compensation is determined in each case on its merits and according to its circumstances,&quot; says Attorney Reif-Liganze, adding that &quot;today, most claims based on medical negligence end in a compromise that weighs the chances and risks that each party has in conducting the procedure.&quot; However, the attorney added that &quot;there are cases in which the procedure ends only with a verdict, in which case, if the claim is not dismissed, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages. For example, in a lawsuit conducted by our firm, the District Court awarded compensation exceeding ten million shekels to a minor who suffered cerebral palsy due to a delay in identifying fetal distress.&quot;
In conclusion
Medical malpractice during childbirth is undoubtedly every family&#39;s nightmare.
In these cases, a proper legal examination of the sequence of events that caused the tragic outcome, by an attorney skilled in handling claims based on medical negligence, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
This is the reason for the prevalence of the eye disease keratoconus in the South
A study has shown that there is a link between the development of the disease and marriage between relatives •
The highest prevalence was found in the Bedouin sector •
Expert: &quot;It is possible that in any sector with many marriages between cousins, we will find a high incidence of the disease.&quot;
Keratoconus is an inherited eye disease that causes some vision impairment.
It is very important to diagnose it as soon as possible, and to find the right solutions to prevent the situation from worsening.
In recent years, several studies have been conducted that help understand how the disease develops, and innovative treatments have been developed.
The new studies provide research support for the suspicion that the eye disease keratoconus is a genetic disease.
A recent study, which dealt with changing the shape of the cornea from a dome to a cone, revealed that the cause of the disease and weakness of the cornea and its distortion of shape is related to an enzymatic imbalance, as a result of which free radicals may damage the proteins in the cornea - and its structure will change.
The source of this enzyme deficiency is genetic, a fact that strengthens the hypothesis that keratoconus is a hereditary disease.
According to Prof. Ariella Gordon-Shagg, head of the Department of Optometric Sciences at Hadassah Academic College, &quot;A study published in the field among Arab students in Haifa found a prevalence of keratoconus of 3.2%.
&quot;The highest prevalence was among students from the Bedouin sector - 20% had keratoconus, but it was a relatively small sample.&quot;
The researcher added that this is not a surprising finding: &quot;There is a high prevalence of keratoconus in the Bedouin sector.
In our studies, we found that consanguineous marriage is a risk factor for keratoconus.
&quot;So in any sector with a lot of marriages between cousins, we might find a high prevalence.&quot;
In this context, it should be noted that this is an important finding in light of the unequivocal conclusion: in cases where there is a family history of keratoconus, all family members should undergo an appropriate eye examination as soon as possible.
According to Erza Fruchter, a B.Sc. clinical optometrist, &quot;There are ten times more visits to the clinic from remote peripheral areas, mainly from the south, compared to the center.&quot;
Fruchter adds that &quot;In the last decade, I have noticed that most patients come from the periphery, especially from the Beer Sheva area.
&quot;This is mainly due to the high prevalence of marriages within the family (especially in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and a lack of awareness of how to properly treat the problem.&quot;
So how is the disease diagnosed?
Fruchter explains that keratoconus usually develops in adolescence or the late teens (ages 15-16 or 20).
The disease involves a decrease in vision, accompanied by an increase in the cylinder.
Keratoconus patients report distorted and/or blurred vision of figures and objects.
These signs worsen as the disease progresses, which usually develops slowly and gradually over years.
However, the disease may also develop rapidly and reach its peak within just a few months.
Many patients also report increased sensitivity to light.
