Senior police officer: &quot;Government policy and goal-setting are needed here&quot;
The Israel Police has launched an operation to eradicate the phenomenon of illegal residents, but there is still a long way to go.
&quot;Today, there is no single factor in the State of Israel that encompasses this entire issue.&quot;
&quot;If we want to address the phenomenon of illegal residents, a government policy is required, from which goals, tasks, and responsibilities must be derived.
&quot;Today, there is no single factor in the State of Israel that encompasses this entire issue,&quot; a senior police officer tells Israel Hayom.
Until a month and a half ago, before the escalation in the security situation, the phenomenon was expressed in about 20 to 30 thousand refugees entering daily through the breaches in the fence.
In addition, between 100,000 and 110,000 Palestinians with work permits enter Israel every day to work through 34 controlled crossings.
It should be noted that Palestinians have been employed in Israel since the end of the Six-Day War, and the number of permits in each sector is limited by a quota determined by the political echelon according to the security, economic, and political situation in the State of Israel.
Permits are issued by the IDF through the Coordination and Liaison Administration.
In light of this, a Sheba is not necessarily a Palestinian whose entry is prohibited due to criminal involvement or connection to terrorist attacks, but in many cases these are Palestinians whose entry is prohibited because they do not meet the permitted permit quota.
It should be emphasized that those who carried out the attacks in Ariel, Dizengoff, and Elad were considered members of the Israeli Security Service, but they were not monitored, because they had not previously committed any criminal offense that required security officials to monitor their movements.
&quot;Therefore, their entry through the breaches in the fence is meaningless,&quot; says a senior security official. &quot;Anyone who wants to carry out an attack can also enter the country through the controlled crossings, and there have been such cases in the past.&quot;
Thousands of arrests
Following the attack in Elad and in light of numerous warnings of attacks, the police launched a large-scale operation to locate illegal residents.
By the end of the week, about 16,000 Shebahim had been arrested.
Of these, about 600 were investigated and criminal cases were opened against them, and about 200 were imprisoned.
According to police prosecution policy, proceedings against illegal residents are only carried out against habitual criminals or people who repeat the act repeatedly (recidivists).
An illegal resident arrested for the first time is interrogated, documented, and returned to the territories.
Sometimes this happens a second time, but only the third time is he arrested, imprisoned, and indicted for illegal residence.
According to the law, if an illegal resident is caught within 50 to 100 meters of either side of the separation fence, he is handled by the military prosecution.
Data received by &quot;Israel Hayom&quot; indicates that in 2021, 40,010 illegal residents, drivers, and overnighters were handled by the police.
7,405 illegal residents were arrested and criminal cases were opened against 19,533.
The number of employers, drivers, and carriers handled by the police in 2021 was 6,537.
469 were arrested, and criminal cases were opened against 5,640.
&quot;The foundations of the Shabachim phenomenon do not depend on the police, nor on the IDF, nor on Israeli society, nor on Palestinian society.&quot;
&quot;They depend on other factors,&quot; says a senior law enforcement official.
&quot;To address the phenomenon, their motivation to go to work in Israel must be eroded, and the Israeli side must charge them a price that will prevent them from crossing the fence.&quot;
Sources involved in the matter claim that the failure to collect the price stems, among other things, from a lack of prison space and the fact that arrests are only made when there are associated offenses or when the person is a recidivist.
Legal sources claim that the decision to charge a fee from the Israeli Security Service only starting from his third arrest was made, among other things, because the courts cannot cope with the number of arrests that are made every day.
&quot;Anyone who examines the punishment will discover that it is not a deterrent.&quot;
There is great complexity.
&quot;Sheba,&quot; says a police source, &quot;is a complex person.&quot;
He could be a father of a family who enters the country to work to earn a few shekels and return.
This is the basic platform, and it is used by many types of &quot;shamers&quot; who enter the country to commit criminal offenses or terrorist attacks.
A defendant can be an adult or a minor.
In the past, the police have caught illegal residents as young as 16, and even children as young as 8 and 10, who are sent by their parents to road junctions to earn a few shekels a day from driving.
&quot;It also makes the matter complicated, because in such cases we have to bring the parents and file charges against them for neglect,&quot; says a senior police officer.
Most Palestinians are employed in Israel in manual labor.
The most unusual are electrical work or advanced construction work.
In the past, there were also local authorities that employed garbage collectors to remove trash, mainly in the north.
Out of 34 crossings, there are about 18 main crossings.
There are crossings for vehicles and goods, there are crossings through which only people pass, and there are crossings that are both.
All crossings are supervised by the IDF and the Crossings Authority.
The Shabachim are usually driven into the country by private drivers, as it is easy money.
&quot;There are those who do this for a living, and there are gangs whose main occupation is transporting &quot;shabhim&quot;,&quot; says a senior police officer. &quot;Usually, most of them are Israeli Arabs, who speak the same language and correspond with them.&quot;
This can range from 100 shekels to 300 shekels per person.
&quot;Registered companies don&#39;t do this, because if the company gets caught, it&#39;s doomed to shut down.&quot;
The police emphasize that under certain conditions, transporting a stolen vehicle can be considered a crime.
&quot;A taxi driver who works with licenses in accordance with licensing and insurance, who picks up Palestinians at arranged points and at fixed times, including an arranged reservation, is not breaking the law,&quot; says a senior police officer. &quot;Anyone who knows he is transporting Palestinians usually picks them up in the dead of night at hidden points, including dropping them off at hidden points.&quot;
&quot;Most of these guys drive with a used car because they know their car will be confiscated, so they prefer to drive in an old car.&quot;
