A look at the &quot;Asaf&quot; facility
Preparing for the next attack: A series of terrorist attacks carried out in the spring by Palestinians and Israeli Arabs, during which 19 people were murdered and about 70 civilians were injured, led the Border Guard to develop a unique technique that trains fighters to attack terrorists within a civilian population and carry out shooting in motion.
Israel Hayom unveiling: A look at the &quot;Asaf&quot; facility
Popular terrorism focuses on harming civilians and aims to undermine the sense of security necessary for a civilian population to lead a normal life.
The severe wave of attacks that occurred this year, with attacks in Be&#39;er Sheva, Hadera, Bnei Brak, Ariel, Elad, and especially the one that occurred in early April on busy Dizengoff Street in the heart of Tel Aviv, by a terrorist who blended into a crowd, led the police to think creatively to develop a tool that would allow them to train fighters to attack terrorists within a civilian population.
The thinking process was led by the Police and Border Guard Training Division.
These were entered into a competition in the various police districts under the title &quot;Commanders Lead Learning,&quot; in which each district was required to develop measures that would help improve the policing and combat skills of fighters, police officers, and commanders.
As part of the competition, and in response to the need to train Border Guard soldiers to fight in moving shooting training and in scenarios of this type, Assaf Ben David, a counter-terrorism instructor for the Jerusalem Border Guard, developed the &quot;Asaf Device,&quot; which consists of a dynamic target, which is attached to a telescopic rod on which a carrier is mounted that can be harnessed to the instructor.
Their servant who guides the bearer to our death, he can practice the warrior standing before him by controlling and moving the target to different sides and ranges.
It should be emphasized that in recent years, Border Guard soldiers have dealt with many terrorist attacks in which the attacker carries out shooting and poses a threat while moving in areas saturated with innocent civilians.
The &quot;Asaf Facility&quot;, in its current version, is based on components and parts that are used in various fields.
For example, the telescopic pole that was upgraded and integrated into the facility was taken from the field of maintenance and cleaning.
Using the facility, it is possible to simulate shooting on the move within a civilian population towards a dynamic target while maintaining eye contact with the object, handling a traffic stop, choosing a path of progress, and executing selective shooting, including practicing preventing harm to uninvolved people.
Sergeant Major Assaf Ben David, after whom the facility is named, says: &quot;The facility we developed is a breakthrough in the learning and training of soldiers and police officers.
The development provides a relevant response to the threats of attribution and simulates the reality on the ground.
&quot;The benefit of development compared to the relatively cheap production cost gives us a significant competitive advantage.&quot;
