Research states: Zoom meetings harm creativity
About 2,100 engineers and academics around the world were asked to develop solutions to the problem – some in video meetings, some in face-to-face meetings •
The result: Virtual meetings hurt creativity and outside-the-box thinking •
Research leader at Columbia University: &quot;Visual focus on the screen impairs the idea generation process&quot; •
Nechama Forta: There is no harm to work productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the effect of meetings via video software on the creativity of participants, compared to meetings held face-to-face.
Unfortunately, it has been found that creativity is indeed compromised in virtual meetings via screens.
The research question - led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University - was whether remote meetings via computer preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or whether the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of the distance.
The research itself began in 2016 but received a major boost in the two years of the coronavirus, during which many employees moved to work from home.
&quot;People in an in-person meeting move around the room, use objects, and use them for creative thinking,&quot; says Brooks.
&quot;In a computer meeting, on the other hand, concentration on maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain.
Visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
&quot;People are more focused on video when interacting, which hurts the broader, more expansive idea generation process.&quot;
Space is shrinking.
To examine the results of the experiment and ensure that they would be repeated, they were tested twice – once at Columbia University and once in real life – on engineers who knew each other from previous acquaintances.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty and students into two parts – in one, the subjects were asked to meet in person and develop solutions to the problem, and in the other, they were asked to do so via computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East, and South Asia were asked to divide themselves in a similar way and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, a decrease in creativity and outside-the-box thinking was found among those who met virtually via video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher who studies ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, in the context of a thinking activity, people often look at their surroundings to help generate ideas, whereas in a video meeting, thinking converges on the screen and does not expand in a way that allows for creativity.
&quot;When people are in the same room, they look around them and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can evoke new associations in them.
&quot;On the other hand, research shows that relationships through a computer change our attention so that we are more focused inward and on the screen, and this reduces innovation and the creation of ideas through looking at the environment and thinking outward.&quot;
There is no harm in critical thinking.
However, before managers rush employees back to the offices, the researchers note that &quot;working via computer did not harm productivity itself or people&#39;s critical thinking about innovative proposals, when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
&quot;That is, the damage is focused solely on creativity and not on other forms of computer work.&quot;
Prof. Ellen Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also doubts the findings.
According to her, &quot;There is a difference between just creativity, like new uses for a Frisbee (one of the research questions; AG) and working solutions.
It is also possible that when employees are more relaxed after getting to know each other, or when they work from home, creativity will improve.&quot;
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson also suggested future research in which such meetings would be interrupted for thinking and wandering around the room to see how this activity would affect the final outcome.
Dr. Olson also suggested that following the study, employees should only return to work for brainstorming sessions, and as a general rule, he suggested not to be alarmed by one study but to conduct further investigation in the field.
&quot;I wouldn&#39;t want workers to be forcibly returned and not be happy. That would be a bigger blow,&quot; he says.
