We checked: What do the side effects after the Corona vaccine mean?
Many people who get vaccinated feel weak, feverish, and tired after receiving the shot, while others feel nothing.
Could this indicate a stronger immune system in those who do experience these symptoms, or is this a baseless rumor?
As more and more people get vaccinated, the lack of information about side effects continues to confuse and create rumors, most of which are untrue.
Are the immune systems of those who developed side effects stronger than those whose bodies reacted less severely to the vaccine, which could perhaps prove that their system is unable to fight off a foreign body that has entered the body?
&quot;There are several levels of reactions to the vaccine,&quot; says Dr. David Dvir, head of the Primary Medicine Department at Meuhedet and a member of the advisory committee for the TCM (Epidemic Treatment Team), and reassures: &quot;Headaches, fatigue, pain in the area, these are the immediate reactions of the immune system.
This is how the body reacts to the entry of a foreign body into the system.&quot;
Is there a relationship between the levels of antibodies that develop and the side effects?
&quot;There is no correlation between feelings and the development of antibodies against the virus.&quot;
About 50%-60% experience side effects, but about 90% develop protection against the virus.
&quot;It was not found that people who developed strong reactions were more protected.&quot;
&quot;The medical literature does not show a correlation between an immediate response and the level of immunity.
In some trials where people also received placebo vaccines, about a quarter of them developed headaches.
This is also a mental component - how the person perceives the vaccine, whether they expect there to be side effects.
&quot;Many of the phenomena that occur could also occur normally, but because the public is immune, they attribute the reaction to the vaccine itself, and this is a bias that is seen regarding vaccines in general - attributing phenomena that occur near the vaccine and are attributed to it.&quot;
According to Dr. Dvir, the causes of the commonly reported symptoms, such as weakness and headaches, are not yet known.
Regarding inflammation of the heart muscle (myocarditis), opinions are divided.
&quot;There are all kinds of theories on the subject, but it should be noted that the virus itself causes higher rates of myocarditis than the vaccine.
&quot;One theory is that it&#39;s a strong immune system response.&quot;
Is it even possible to assess the strength of an immune system?
&quot;When students were exposed to the flu virus, it was shown that those who did not sleep or were under higher stress were more vulnerable to infection.
Apart from this, there are laboratory parameters that test the immune system or its components.
When there is a decline in the immune system, you see it immediately.
People get a lot of viral or infectious diseases.
It&#39;s not like someone is walking around with a weak immune system and isn&#39;t aware of it.
These are people who come for checkups because of repeated episodes of infectious diseases, and what affects the system are banal things: stress, nutrition, sleep.
&quot;By the way, we also don&#39;t want an immune system that is too strong, because it can cause autoimmune diseases.&quot;
MRNA vaccines will soon appear in additional contexts, thanks to the extensive knowledge that has accumulated about them in recent times.
&quot;There is no doubt that the door will be opened for other vaccines of this type.&quot;
This technology is being tested for many uses beyond vaccines - for treatments of oncological diseases, for example.
Their effectiveness is that the substance remains in the body for a very short time - it enters, does its job, and then breaks down.
This technology is not new, but it has received a serious boost due to the very great need for a rapid vaccine.
&quot;Now, for example, we know that a three-week interval between doses is too small, and some vaccine experts claim that after a third dose we may not need another vaccine in the near term, so it is unclear whether we are going to a situation where we need to vaccinate every six months or whether the third dose will provide a greater interval.&quot;
